      "question": "If the prime factorization of a positive integer $n$ is given by $n = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^k$ and it is known that $n$ is a multiple of $150$, then the smallest possible value of the non-negative integer $k$ is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Find the prime factorization of $150$.",
          "Express $n$ in terms of its prime factors.",
          "Use the definition of a multiple to establish the condition for $k$.",
          "Compare the exponents of the primes to find the smallest value of $k$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$150 = 15 \times 10 = (3 \times 5) \times (2 \times 5) = 2^1 \times 3^1 \times 5^2 \\ \\text{Given } n = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^k \\ \\text{For } n \\text{ to be a multiple of } 150, \\text{ the exponent of each prime factor in } n \\text{ must be greater than or equal to the exponent of the same prime in } 150. \\ \\text{For factor } 2: 3 \\geq 1 \\text{ (True)} \\ \\text{For factor } 3: 2 \\geq 1 \\text{ (True)} \\ \\text{For factor } 5: k \\geq 2 \\ \\text{The smallest integer } k \\text{ satisfying } k \\geq 2 \\text{ is } 2.$"
      },
